Making Maps in R

Matthew L. Sisk

June, 2018

Loading Spatial Data

Loading spatial data in R is relatively simple. First, the best package to use for incorporating spatial information is rgdal. This package is R bindings for the Geospatial Data Abstraction Library, which is the basis for most open-source GIS packages. This is what we will use for opening pre-existing spatial data in the form of shapefiles

library(rgdal)

In rgdal, there are two different tools for opening raster and vector data. readOGR is the command for loading vector data. It is a little different than other read commands in r in that is wants the path (called the dsn) separate from the filename

districts <- readOGR(dsn="SampleData", layer = "City_Council_Districts", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)  
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "/home/matthew/GIT/R_Scripts/Data-Viz-2018-Fall/Week03/Demonstrations/SampleData", layer: "City_Council_Districts"
## with 6 features
## It has 14 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  OBJECTID_1 OBJECTID

When we have loaded the shapefile, it gives sone basic information about the number of features, the number of fields and the type of data. Remember that the information in the table is separate from the points that make up the feature. This is a polygon layer. We can access the table using the @data call

head(districts@data)

Loading spatial data from a table

Often, you will not get spatial data as part of an existing shapefile. You may instead get a table with latitude and longitude coordinates (Or street addresses, which we will get to in a different demonstration). Hear, let’s load a table that has latitude and longitude coordinates

facilities.points <- read.csv("SampleData/Public_Facilities.csv")

Now, in order to covert this into something we can map, we to define it as a SpatialPointsDataFrame. The arguments are basically, the coodinates, the rest of the data and what coordinate system it uses. The one listed here is for latitude and longitude and is the most common you will use.

facilities.spatial <- SpatialPointsDataFrame(coords = facilities.points[,c("Lon","Lat")], data = facilities.points,
                             proj4string = CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84"))

This now converts it over the a spatialPointsDataFrame

Creating Static Maps

Once we have spatial data loaded in R, we can create maps easily. We can just use the base R plot to create one, but this is pretty basic

plot(districts)

Alternatively, there are a few packages built for creating maps in R. Probably the most commonly use is ggmap, which is designed to be like ggplot for spatial data. The difficulty in using ggmap is that it only accepts a dataframe as an input, so we have to convert our hard earned SpatialDataFrames back to normal dataframes using the fortify command and then join all of the attributes back on.

library(ggmap)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Google Maps API Terms of Service: http://developers.google.com/maps/terms.
## Please cite ggmap if you use it: see citation("ggmap") for details.

We can now use the same sort of syntax we would with a normal ggplot to create maps.

The coord_fixed just prevents the map from becoming distorted if we resize the window. It is a good idea to keep it there.

districts2 <- fortify(districts, region = 'Dist')
districts2  <- merge(districts2, districts@data, by.x = 'id', by.y = 'Dist')

ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = districts2, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group)) + 
  coord_fixed(1.3)

We can now color the map based of off the district.

ggplot(data = districts2) + geom_polygon(aes(x = long, y = lat, fill = id, group = group), color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3)

We can now add other layers just like we would in normal ggplot

ggplot(data = districts2) + geom_polygon(aes(x = long, y = lat, fill = id, group = group), color = "white") + 
  coord_fixed(1.3)+
  geom_point(data = facilities.points, aes(x = Lon, y = Lat, group = POPL_TYPE, col = POPL_TYPE))

spplot

Another option is the spplot tool from the sp package(which is automatically loaded with rgdal). Spplot has the advantage of working directly with the spatial objects(no conversion necessary) and is really good at creating colored maps from numerical values. This shows how quickly you can create a map using just the area of each city council district.

spplot(districts, "ShapeSTLen")

Downloading Basemaps

If it is hard to visualize where there disctricts or points are, you can also download a static version of one of the common webmaps to use as a basemap. using get_map from the ggmap package will basically cache a single image for you to use. Do note that these basemap layers are usually free to use for academic purposes, but you should look into their terms of service before using them in commercial applications.

base.map <- get_map("South Bend, IN", zoom = 12, maptype = "roadmap")
ggmap(base.map)+
  geom_point(data = facilities.points, aes(x = Lon, y = Lat, group = POPL_TYPE, col = POPL_TYPE)) 
## Warning: Removed 16 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
